1
00:00:02,542 --> 00:00:06,208
<i>Captain's log,</i>
<i>Stardate 42859.2.</i>

2
00:00:06,250 --> 00:00:08,041
<i>We are in orbit</i>
<i>around Antede 3</i>

3
00:00:08,083 --> 00:00:10,417
<i>awaiting the arrival</i>
<i>of two dignitaries.</i>

4
00:00:10,458 --> 00:00:11,750
<i>Our mission is</i>
<i>to escort them</i>

5
00:00:11,792 --> 00:00:14,000
<i>to a conference</i>
<i>on planet Pacifica</i>

6
00:00:14,041 --> 00:00:15,959
<i>where they will be given</i>
<i>the opportunity</i>

7
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:18,000
<i>to join the Federation.</i>

8
00:00:22,166 --> 00:00:24,500
I thought you might find
this interesting, Mr. Crusher.

9
00:00:24,542 --> 00:00:27,583
Few humans have seen
an Antedian in the flesh.

10
00:00:34,875 --> 00:00:36,041
Welcome.

11
00:00:36,083 --> 00:00:37,417
I'm Jean-Luc Picard

12
00:00:37,458 --> 00:00:40,625
captain of
the<i> Enterprise.</i>

13
00:00:48,333 --> 00:00:50,375
Are they
all right, sir?

14
00:00:50,417 --> 00:00:51,542
Yes.

15
00:00:51,583 --> 00:00:53,166
This is their
preferred way

16
00:00:53,208 --> 00:00:54,709
of space travel.

17
00:00:54,750 --> 00:00:57,375
PULASKI:
Their physical condition
is good enough,

18
00:00:57,417 --> 00:01:00,166
considering
the circumstances.

19
00:01:00,208 --> 00:01:03,625
It is a self-induced
catatonic state--

20
00:01:03,667 --> 00:01:05,208
their way of dealing

21
00:01:05,250 --> 00:01:07,500
with the trauma
of spaceflight.

22
00:01:07,542 --> 00:01:09,542
Will we try
to revive them?

23
00:01:09,583 --> 00:01:12,250
No. Not until we reach
the Pacifica conference

24
00:01:12,291 --> 00:01:13,792
three days
from now.

25
00:01:13,834 --> 00:01:15,834
Doctor, have you prepared
a sick bay facility

26
00:01:15,875 --> 00:01:17,583
to accommodate
our guests?

27
00:01:17,625 --> 00:01:19,583
Well as soon as I can make
some adjustments.

28
00:01:19,625 --> 00:01:22,208
Their physiology
is unusual.

29
00:01:22,250 --> 00:01:24,208
You can store them
for a few hours?

30
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:26,333
Sure, I'll have them
kept here out of the way.

31
00:01:26,375 --> 00:01:27,792
Mr. Worf,
provide security.

32
00:01:27,834 --> 00:01:30,000
WORF:
Aye, sir.

33
00:01:30,041 --> 00:01:33,166
What's in that
container?

34
00:01:33,208 --> 00:01:34,917
Vermicula.

35
00:01:34,959 --> 00:01:36,458
It's their food.

36
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:39,125
When they come out of stasis,
they'll be very hungry.

37
00:01:42,041 --> 00:01:43,375
They eat this?

38
00:01:43,417 --> 00:01:45,583
In great quantities.

39
00:01:51,083 --> 00:01:53,375
What a handsome race.

40
00:02:01,125 --> 00:02:04,125
So what did you think
of the Antedians, Wesley?

41
00:02:04,166 --> 00:02:07,750
They are... rather
strange looking, Commander.

42
00:02:07,792 --> 00:02:09,750
Judging a being by its
physical appearance

43
00:02:09,792 --> 00:02:12,750
is the last major
human prejudice, Wesley.

44
00:02:12,792 --> 00:02:14,750
Point is well taken,
Mr. Data.

45
00:02:14,792 --> 00:02:16,041
I'm sure that
to the Antedians,

46
00:02:16,083 --> 00:02:17,834
we are equally
unattractive.

47
00:02:17,875 --> 00:02:19,458
Captain,
we are being hailed

48
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:22,500
by a small transport vessel,
just coming into range.

49
00:02:22,542 --> 00:02:23,875
Oh, my God.

50
00:02:25,750 --> 00:02:27,750
What's the problem?

51
00:02:28,709 --> 00:02:30,333
What's<i> she</i> doing here?

52
00:02:30,375 --> 00:02:31,583
WESLEY:
On screen, Captain.

53
00:02:31,625 --> 00:02:33,208
<i>Starship Enterprise,</i>
come in.

54
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:35,000
RIKER:
We have you on viewer, pilot.

55
00:02:35,041 --> 00:02:36,917
<i>Enterprise,</i>
I have a passenger.

56
00:02:36,959 --> 00:02:38,709
A V.I.P. passenger
who I--

57
00:02:38,750 --> 00:02:40,125
Oh, let me talk
to them.

58
00:02:40,166 --> 00:02:42,375
I'm sure I'm more
articulate than that.

59
00:02:42,417 --> 00:02:43,625
Mother.

60
00:02:43,667 --> 00:02:45,291
DATA:
Captain,
we are receiving

61
00:02:45,333 --> 00:02:47,583
Starfleet orders
granting a Lwaxana...

62
00:02:47,625 --> 00:02:49,083
Lwaxana Troi!

63
00:02:49,125 --> 00:02:50,500
A daughter of
the Fifth House,

64
00:02:50,542 --> 00:02:52,959
holder of the
Sacred Chalice of Riix,

65
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:55,750
heir to the Holy Rings
of Betazed.

66
00:02:55,792 --> 00:02:57,917
...full ambassadorial
status, sir.

67
00:02:57,959 --> 00:03:00,250
It looks like it's back
into that dress uniform, sir.

68
00:03:00,291 --> 00:03:01,834
And yours as well,
Commander.

69
00:03:01,875 --> 00:03:03,250
She is listed
as representing

70
00:03:03,291 --> 00:03:05,500
the Betazed government
at the conference.

71
00:03:05,542 --> 00:03:08,166
Mother, please,
don't do this to me.

72
00:03:08,208 --> 00:03:10,625
LWAXANA:
Do what to you,
little one?

73
00:03:10,667 --> 00:03:13,125
Oh! Jean-Luc,

74
00:03:13,166 --> 00:03:15,709
what naughty
thoughts.

75
00:03:15,750 --> 00:03:18,917
But how wonderful you still
think of me like that.

76
00:03:42,125 --> 00:03:46,500
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

77
00:03:46,542 --> 00:03:50,834
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship Enterprise.</i>

78
00:03:50,875 --> 00:03:52,375
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

79
00:03:52,417 --> 00:03:56,458
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds,</i>

80
00:03:56,500 --> 00:04:01,000
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations,</i>

81
00:04:01,041 --> 00:04:05,166
<i>to boldly go</i>
<i>where no one has gone before.</i>

82
00:05:05,125 --> 00:05:08,458
It's so like my mother
to do the unexpected.

83
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:11,291
Well, it will
be... pleasant

84
00:05:11,333 --> 00:05:13,750
to have her as a guest
of the<i> Enterprise</i> again.

85
00:05:15,792 --> 00:05:17,333
Energize.

86
00:05:24,542 --> 00:05:26,709
Legs!
Where are the legs?

87
00:05:26,750 --> 00:05:29,500
Where they belong, Mother,
right under you.

88
00:05:29,542 --> 00:05:31,458
Oh, I hate that.

89
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:34,875
I will never completely trust
this device, Jean-Luc.

90
00:05:34,917 --> 00:05:37,125
<i>Captain Picard,</i> Mother.

91
00:05:37,166 --> 00:05:38,583
(<i> startled cry</i> )

92
00:05:40,750 --> 00:05:41,959
Explain to her.

93
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
I'm sorry they startled
you Mrs. Troi.

94
00:05:44,041 --> 00:05:45,375
They're Antedian
delegates.

95
00:05:45,417 --> 00:05:46,917
They're being stored
here temporarily.

96
00:05:46,959 --> 00:05:48,583
Delegates?

97
00:05:48,625 --> 00:05:50,083
Last time I saw
something like that,

98
00:05:50,125 --> 00:05:51,709
it was being served
on a plate.

99
00:05:55,792 --> 00:05:57,667
Darling.

100
00:05:59,250 --> 00:06:00,667
Ah.

101
00:06:00,709 --> 00:06:02,250
LWAXANA:
Well, well, well.

102
00:06:02,291 --> 00:06:03,583
And<i> you</i> Jean-Luc,

103
00:06:03,625 --> 00:06:06,709
I wasn't aware you had
such handsome legs.

104
00:06:06,750 --> 00:06:08,417
My valet is waiting.

105
00:06:08,458 --> 00:06:10,583
You may beam him
aboard now.

106
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:17,959
You remember Mr. Homn,
of course.

107
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,875
It would be hard
to forget Mr. Homn.

108
00:06:20,917 --> 00:06:22,583
I've retained
his services despite

109
00:06:22,625 --> 00:06:24,125
the outlandishly
lustful thoughts

110
00:06:24,166 --> 00:06:26,000
he spews
in my direction.

111
00:06:26,041 --> 00:06:27,667
You can put
that down, Homn.

112
00:06:27,709 --> 00:06:29,750
We can't deny the captain
the honor

113
00:06:29,792 --> 00:06:32,542
of carrying
my belongings.

114
00:06:32,583 --> 00:06:35,959
I will not interfere with
Mr. Homn's duties this time.

115
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:37,250
Oh, now,
that's not what

116
00:06:37,291 --> 00:06:39,166
you're really thinking,
Jean-Luc.

117
00:06:39,208 --> 00:06:41,583
You forget,
I'm a telepath.

118
00:06:41,625 --> 00:06:43,667
Mrs. Troi, since this
is obviously

119
00:06:43,709 --> 00:06:45,875
significant to you...

120
00:06:49,125 --> 00:06:51,375
I'll--

121
00:06:55,583 --> 00:06:57,542
I'll carry it.

122
00:07:06,375 --> 00:07:09,375
Just down this corridor.

123
00:07:09,417 --> 00:07:11,917
LWAXANA:<i> </i>
<i>He has nice legs too,</i>
<i>little one.</i>

124
00:07:11,959 --> 00:07:13,792
<i>Is he still yours?</i>

125
00:07:13,834 --> 00:07:16,709
<i>Humans no longer own</i>
<i>each other that way, Mother.</i>

126
00:07:16,750 --> 00:07:19,291
Really?

127
00:07:19,333 --> 00:07:23,166
That's a custom we may
have to introduce again.

128
00:07:28,917 --> 00:07:30,291
Thank you.

129
00:07:30,333 --> 00:07:32,250
Glad to help.

130
00:07:36,083 --> 00:07:38,333
Well, I trust you will
be comfortable here.

131
00:07:38,375 --> 00:07:39,667
If you will
excuse me...

132
00:07:39,709 --> 00:07:41,917
Uh, I am serving
a Betazoid

133
00:07:41,959 --> 00:07:44,709
dinner of greeting
tonight, Captain.

134
00:07:44,750 --> 00:07:47,375
It is an ambassadorial
function.

135
00:07:47,417 --> 00:07:49,458
It sounds delightful.

136
00:07:53,625 --> 00:07:56,083
He's a fine man.

137
00:07:56,125 --> 00:07:58,500
Solid, he's reliable.

138
00:08:00,542 --> 00:08:02,291
He's a little bit
on the stuffy side

139
00:08:02,333 --> 00:08:05,000
but, uh, all in all,
he's not that bad.

140
00:08:05,041 --> 00:08:06,417
I can't believe you,
Mother.

141
00:08:06,458 --> 00:08:09,250
You sound like you're
sizing up a commodity.

142
00:08:09,291 --> 00:08:11,041
But that's exactly
what men are,

143
00:08:11,083 --> 00:08:13,792
darling,
especially human men.

144
00:08:14,959 --> 00:08:18,000
Was your father ever
unhappy with me?

145
00:08:18,041 --> 00:08:19,625
No.

146
00:08:19,667 --> 00:08:21,291
He worshipped you.

147
00:08:21,333 --> 00:08:23,000
But I don't think
I'll ever learn

148
00:08:23,041 --> 00:08:24,667
to see men
the way you do.

149
00:08:25,709 --> 00:08:28,625
You will as
you mature, darling.

150
00:08:28,667 --> 00:08:31,792
And the men in your life
are going to bless you for it.

151
00:08:33,125 --> 00:08:35,208
You're so beautiful.

152
00:08:37,875 --> 00:08:41,125
And she actually complimented
Captain Picard on his legs?

153
00:08:42,125 --> 00:08:43,291
I would have
thought a telepath

154
00:08:43,333 --> 00:08:45,083
would be more
discreet, sir.

155
00:08:45,125 --> 00:08:46,834
RIKER:
Exactly the opposite.
She knows what's on your mind

156
00:08:46,875 --> 00:08:49,917
and she lets you know
what's on hers.

157
00:08:49,959 --> 00:08:52,625
(laughing)
PICARD: Gentlemen...

158
00:08:58,166 --> 00:08:59,959
I think we must not
lose sight of the fact

159
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,500
that we are talking
about someone

160
00:09:01,542 --> 00:09:04,166
who has been granted
ambassadorial rank,

161
00:09:04,208 --> 00:09:06,625
even though
she may appear...

162
00:09:06,667 --> 00:09:08,333
somewhat eccentric.

163
00:09:08,375 --> 00:09:10,291
Lwaxana Troi must
be treated with

164
00:09:10,333 --> 00:09:13,417
the appropriate respect.
Is that understood?

165
00:09:16,583 --> 00:09:18,834
Picard to Pulaski.
Yes, Captain?

166
00:09:18,875 --> 00:09:22,375
When did you last look in
on the Antedian guests?

167
00:09:22,417 --> 00:09:24,333
Doing so right now,
Captain.

168
00:09:24,375 --> 00:09:26,333
Are they still catatonic?

169
00:09:26,375 --> 00:09:28,500
Status of the beings
is unchanged.

170
00:09:30,375 --> 00:09:32,500
Pulse, still steady.

171
00:09:33,709 --> 00:09:37,166
Respiration...
normal for them.

172
00:09:37,208 --> 00:09:39,208
Understood.
Keep me informed.

173
00:09:39,250 --> 00:09:40,375
Picard out.

174
00:09:40,417 --> 00:09:42,583
I'll be
in my quarters.

175
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:46,166
It will be a dress uniform
dinner, gentlemen.

176
00:09:46,208 --> 00:09:47,542
Sir?

177
00:09:51,083 --> 00:09:54,166
To which dinner was
the captain referring, sir?

178
00:09:54,208 --> 00:09:57,208
Nothing I've been invited to.
Any of you?

179
00:10:04,709 --> 00:10:06,583
Very interesting.

180
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:19,291
Doctor?

181
00:10:19,333 --> 00:10:20,542
You're not attending
the dinner

182
00:10:20,583 --> 00:10:22,250
with the rest
of us this evening?

183
00:10:22,291 --> 00:10:25,041
I've already eaten,
but thanks, Captain.

184
00:11:21,291 --> 00:11:23,875
I seem to be
a little early.

185
00:11:27,166 --> 00:11:30,208
I'm sure the others
will be here soon.

186
00:11:34,208 --> 00:11:35,333
The other officers--

187
00:11:35,375 --> 00:11:37,375
Commander Riker,
Counselor Troi?

188
00:11:50,041 --> 00:11:52,000
Hello, Jean-Luc.

189
00:11:54,792 --> 00:11:57,458
So glad you could come.

190
00:12:10,250 --> 00:12:12,000
A toast,
to Earth men

191
00:12:12,041 --> 00:12:14,208
who, despite their
many faults,

192
00:12:14,250 --> 00:12:15,458
have that
unique ability

193
00:12:15,500 --> 00:12:17,875
to charm women
of all races

194
00:12:17,917 --> 00:12:20,709
in all corners
of the galaxy.

195
00:12:22,834 --> 00:12:24,917
Speaking on behalf
of men of Earth,

196
00:12:24,959 --> 00:12:27,083
which is indeed
an awesome responsibility,

197
00:12:27,125 --> 00:12:29,000
I thank you.

198
00:12:39,542 --> 00:12:41,667
I know what you're
thinking, Captain.

199
00:12:41,709 --> 00:12:43,375
You do?

200
00:12:43,417 --> 00:12:44,709
You're wondering
whether I'm seeing

201
00:12:44,750 --> 00:12:48,458
any other man...
on a serious basis.

202
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:50,500
Well, actually,
I wasn't, uh--

203
00:12:50,542 --> 00:12:53,083
Ah, I wouldn't worry
about it, Jean-Luc.

204
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:56,500
Competition seems
to bring out

205
00:12:56,542 --> 00:12:59,291
the best in
the human male.

206
00:13:04,792 --> 00:13:09,000
The fact is,
I, um... uh...

207
00:13:09,041 --> 00:13:12,083
I was not expecting
this, uh, this setting.

208
00:13:12,125 --> 00:13:14,458
I had assumed that
my senior bridge officers

209
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,000
would be attending.

210
00:13:16,041 --> 00:13:17,291
You never assume
anything

211
00:13:17,333 --> 00:13:19,875
where Lwaxana Troi
is concerned.

212
00:13:19,917 --> 00:13:23,458
Betazoid women are
full of surprises.

213
00:13:29,333 --> 00:13:31,500
Ah, strange.

214
00:13:33,250 --> 00:13:35,750
I'm not really
very hungry tonight.

215
00:13:37,125 --> 00:13:39,792
I wonder what's made me
lose my appetite.

216
00:13:39,834 --> 00:13:42,166
Any ideas?

217
00:13:42,208 --> 00:13:43,750
(<i> gong chiming</i> )

218
00:13:46,834 --> 00:13:48,667
Of course. You're giving
thanks for your food.

219
00:13:48,709 --> 00:13:50,875
I had forgotten
about that.

220
00:13:53,083 --> 00:13:56,834
I wonder how many other
cultures have similar customs.

221
00:13:58,417 --> 00:13:59,875
Uh, I don't know.

222
00:14:01,834 --> 00:14:04,083
Well, let's find out.

223
00:14:04,125 --> 00:14:06,709
Commander Data?
Yes, Captain.

224
00:14:06,750 --> 00:14:10,417
Mrs. Troi and I are having
a very interesting discussion

225
00:14:10,458 --> 00:14:14,750
about various societies'
ways of giving thanks.

226
00:14:14,792 --> 00:14:17,917
The Betazoids' use of
the chime, for instance.

227
00:14:17,959 --> 00:14:19,834
The use of the chime
is quite unique,

228
00:14:19,875 --> 00:14:21,583
but not at all
dissimilar

229
00:14:21,625 --> 00:14:23,417
to the Ooolans
of Marejaretus 6,

230
00:14:23,458 --> 00:14:26,083
who use two large stones
which are continuously

231
00:14:26,125 --> 00:14:27,834
struck together during
the meal.

232
00:14:27,875 --> 00:14:30,583
Those at the dinner must eat
until the stones are broken.

233
00:14:30,625 --> 00:14:32,500
Or the oligarchy
at Atifs 4,

234
00:14:32,542 --> 00:14:33,625
which requires a young--

235
00:14:33,667 --> 00:14:35,375
Data,
this is fascinating.

236
00:14:35,417 --> 00:14:37,542
Don't you agree,
Mrs. Troi?

237
00:14:37,583 --> 00:14:39,250
Commander, if your
duties permit,

238
00:14:39,291 --> 00:14:41,625
why don't you
join us for dessert?

239
00:14:41,667 --> 00:14:44,583
I'm sure that Mrs. Troi
would much appreciate

240
00:14:44,625 --> 00:14:46,625
the pleasure of your company.
What?

241
00:14:46,667 --> 00:14:49,000
Indeed, sir.
I'm on my way.

242
00:14:49,041 --> 00:14:51,250
Data out.

243
00:14:51,291 --> 00:14:52,834
How could you
possibly think

244
00:14:52,875 --> 00:14:55,125
I would want to share
our special time together

245
00:14:55,166 --> 00:14:57,917
with that-- that--
that robot of yours?

246
00:14:57,959 --> 00:15:02,000
Because of Data's wonderful
after-dinner conversation.

247
00:15:02,041 --> 00:15:05,667
His anecdotes are the stuff
of legends aboard this ship.

248
00:15:07,875 --> 00:15:10,417
So, by using
the square root of pi

249
00:15:10,458 --> 00:15:12,583
and multiplying it by
nine to the third power,

250
00:15:12,625 --> 00:15:14,709
I was able to
accurately calculate

251
00:15:14,750 --> 00:15:16,667
the distance between
the Omicron system

