00:29:40,375 --> 00:29:42,417
Leaving, Dix?
Uh-huh.

511
00:29:42,458 --> 00:29:44,375
You're not going
to Rex's bar, are you?

512
00:29:44,417 --> 00:29:46,625
Rex's bar.
Why do you ask?

513
00:29:46,667 --> 00:29:49,500
It's one of the messages
I left on your desk.

514
00:29:49,542 --> 00:29:51,625
Well, that sounds like
an excellent idea.

515
00:29:54,125 --> 00:29:55,750
Would you care
to join me?

516
00:29:55,792 --> 00:29:58,792
<i>Me?</i> Have a drink
with<i> you?</i>

517
00:29:58,834 --> 00:30:00,000
Why not?

518
00:30:00,041 --> 00:30:01,667
There ain't no
"why not" about it.

519
00:30:01,709 --> 00:30:04,583
It's just that this is
the first time you ever asked.

520
00:30:04,625 --> 00:30:06,417
Is that a problem?

521
00:30:06,458 --> 00:30:08,083
Not for me.

522
00:30:08,125 --> 00:30:10,125
But you better
take this.

523
00:30:15,250 --> 00:30:16,875
Why?

524
00:30:16,917 --> 00:30:18,875
Because if we're
going to Rex's bar,

525
00:30:18,917 --> 00:30:20,917
you're gonna
need it.

526
00:30:35,834 --> 00:30:40,083
(<i> conversational chatter,</i>
<i>laughter )</i>

527
00:31:01,583 --> 00:31:04,834
Hey, Dix, what do you know
and what do you say?

528
00:31:04,875 --> 00:31:06,208
See this?

529
00:31:06,250 --> 00:31:09,166
Germany's getting ready
to invade England.

530
00:31:09,208 --> 00:31:11,834
Who's gonna stop 'em?
Somebody better.

531
00:31:11,875 --> 00:31:13,583
As long as it isn't us.

532
00:31:13,625 --> 00:31:15,250
The last thing America
needs to do

533
00:31:15,291 --> 00:31:17,500
is fight in another
world war.

534
00:31:17,542 --> 00:31:21,208
Actually, the second world war,
although disastrous,

535
00:31:21,250 --> 00:31:23,834
did end with the United States
taking its place

536
00:31:23,875 --> 00:31:26,166
as a dominant world power
and cultural influence

537
00:31:26,208 --> 00:31:28,125
in the second half of
the 20th century.

538
00:31:28,166 --> 00:31:30,875
Additionally,
that war was a catalyst

539
00:31:30,917 --> 00:31:32,834
of technological
advancement.

540
00:31:32,875 --> 00:31:35,834
Developments in rocketry
and fission

541
00:31:35,875 --> 00:31:38,917
resonate on into
the 24th century.

542
00:31:38,959 --> 00:31:41,709
I don't know if I should
pour you one, Dix.

543
00:31:41,750 --> 00:31:44,041
Sounds like you got
a snootful already.

544
00:31:44,917 --> 00:31:47,333
What's this?
The usual.

545
00:31:47,375 --> 00:31:48,625
Uh-huh. Ah, yes,
now let me see.

546
00:31:48,667 --> 00:31:51,000
That would be, uh,
scotch, neat.

547
00:31:51,041 --> 00:31:52,333
What else?

548
00:31:59,500 --> 00:32:01,417
And for the lady?

549
00:32:03,500 --> 00:32:04,917
Rye and ginger.

550
00:32:27,125 --> 00:32:28,458
Money.

551
00:32:28,500 --> 00:32:29,959
I keep forgetting
the need to carry money.

552
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:32,709
I must remember not to let
this happen again.

553
00:32:32,750 --> 00:32:35,500
Right, I don't mind you
being on the cuff,

554
00:32:35,542 --> 00:32:37,834
but you're up the sleeve
halfway to my collar.

555
00:32:37,875 --> 00:32:40,667
Is that why you wanted
to see me, about my bar bill?

556
00:32:40,709 --> 00:32:44,583
No, it's on account
of... Jimmy Cuzzo.

557
00:32:44,625 --> 00:32:48,250
Jimmy Cuzzo--
I know that name.

558
00:32:48,291 --> 00:32:51,333
He's why I gave you
the gun.

559
00:32:51,375 --> 00:32:55,959
What was the name of
that case he was involved in?

560
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:58,125
<i>The Parrot's Claw.</i>

561
00:32:58,166 --> 00:32:59,709
MADELINE:
Geez, Dix.

562
00:32:59,750 --> 00:33:03,458
Cuzzo is the guy who
iced Marty O'farron.

563
00:33:03,500 --> 00:33:05,583
They never would've nailed him
if it hadn't been for you.

564
00:33:05,625 --> 00:33:07,959
Your testimony
got him "arranged."

565
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:11,834
Yeah.
Yours and mine.

566
00:33:11,875 --> 00:33:13,333
So you brought me here

567
00:33:13,375 --> 00:33:16,458
because<i> you</i> didn't want
to face him alone.

568
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:18,625
I don't want
to face him at all.

569
00:33:18,667 --> 00:33:20,583
I'm hoping that
seeing us together

570
00:33:20,625 --> 00:33:22,291
will slow him up
long enough

571
00:33:22,333 --> 00:33:24,208
to get some things
straight.

572
00:33:24,250 --> 00:33:25,917
And if it doesn't?

573
00:33:25,959 --> 00:33:28,166
Then you just have
to kill him.

574
00:33:33,500 --> 00:33:35,917
Bridge, this is
Dr. Pulaski.

575
00:33:35,959 --> 00:33:37,458
We've just completed
the transfer.

576
00:33:37,500 --> 00:33:40,625
The Antedians
are now in sick bay.

577
00:33:40,667 --> 00:33:42,583
Acknowledged,
Doctor.

578
00:33:45,333 --> 00:33:47,083
Mother, what are you
doing here?

579
00:33:47,125 --> 00:33:48,875
You can't just
stroll onto the bridge

580
00:33:48,917 --> 00:33:50,375
whenever you feel
like it.

581
00:33:50,417 --> 00:33:52,000
I didn't just
stroll on, dear.

582
00:33:52,041 --> 00:33:54,750
I took that "turbotube,"
or whatever you call it.

583
00:33:54,792 --> 00:33:56,959
Uh, the captain's
not here?

584
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:00,083
Um, he is busy
elsewhere, ma'am.

585
00:34:00,125 --> 00:34:02,041
Oh, well...

586
00:34:02,083 --> 00:34:04,375
I have other
interests as well.

587
00:34:04,417 --> 00:34:06,542
<i>You're scheming</i>
<i>something, Mother.</i>

588
00:34:06,583 --> 00:34:09,000
<i>Don't try to fool me,</i>
<i>I can tell.</i>

589
00:34:09,041 --> 00:34:10,959
<i>You're always so</i>
<i>melodramatic, little one.</i>

590
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:14,625
<i>I'm not scheming,</i>
<i>I'm deciding.</i>

591
00:34:17,458 --> 00:34:19,166
<i>Mother, not him.</i>

592
00:34:19,208 --> 00:34:22,041
<i>And why not him?</i>

593
00:34:22,083 --> 00:34:23,625
<i>He's adorable.</i>

594
00:34:34,333 --> 00:34:36,542
Pulaski to bridge.
Riker here.

595
00:34:36,583 --> 00:34:38,875
The Antedians
are coming around.

596
00:34:38,917 --> 00:34:42,083
They are currently in the early
stages of posthibernation.

597
00:34:42,125 --> 00:34:44,125
How long until
they're fully conscious?

598
00:34:44,166 --> 00:34:46,875
I guess it to be
a matter of hours now.

599
00:34:46,917 --> 00:34:48,417
Very well, I'll
inform the captain.

600
00:34:48,458 --> 00:34:50,375
If you'll
excuse me, ma'am.

601
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:53,417
You're going
to see the captain?

602
00:34:53,458 --> 00:34:55,417
But I thought he was tied up
on ship's business.

603
00:34:55,458 --> 00:34:56,834
In a manner
of speaking, he is.

604
00:34:56,875 --> 00:34:58,083
I'm not going to be
disturbing him.

605
00:34:58,125 --> 00:35:00,000
I'll just give him
the message.

606
00:35:00,041 --> 00:35:03,166
Oh.
Excellent timing.

607
00:35:03,208 --> 00:35:05,417
Then you may also
inform him about us.

608
00:35:05,458 --> 00:35:07,208
<i>Us</i> ?
You don't mind

609
00:35:07,250 --> 00:35:10,041
if I let our ship's crew
know first, do you, William?

610
00:35:10,083 --> 00:35:13,041
Uh, friends,
dear friends...

611
00:35:13,083 --> 00:35:14,542
You are all invited

612
00:35:14,583 --> 00:35:17,917
to a prestigious occasion
on the planet Pacifica.

613
00:35:17,959 --> 00:35:20,166
No.
There...

614
00:35:20,208 --> 00:35:23,458
on the shores
of the western sea,

615
00:35:23,500 --> 00:35:27,041
in a traditional
Betazoid ceremony,

616
00:35:27,083 --> 00:35:30,041
your Commander Riker
and I will be joined

617
00:35:30,083 --> 00:35:33,333
in the union
of matrimony.

618
00:35:36,125 --> 00:35:37,333
Married?

619
00:35:37,375 --> 00:35:40,125
Until death
us do part.

620
00:35:50,917 --> 00:35:53,375
Mrs. Troi, I don't know
how to tell you this--

621
00:35:53,417 --> 00:35:55,041
Oh, I know how
you feel, dear.

622
00:35:55,083 --> 00:35:57,250
You're overwhelmed
with excitement.

623
00:35:57,291 --> 00:36:00,542
Oh, believe me,
I understand.

624
00:36:00,583 --> 00:36:02,041
We'll talk about
the details later.

625
00:36:02,083 --> 00:36:04,875
Right now, there are
preparations to be made.

626
00:36:08,750 --> 00:36:09,959
Why did you stop me?

627
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:11,333
Somebody needs
to set her straight.

628
00:36:11,375 --> 00:36:13,125
I think I'll leave that
to the Captain.

629
00:36:13,166 --> 00:36:14,333
Coward.

630
00:36:14,375 --> 00:36:17,166
Commander...

631
00:36:17,208 --> 00:36:19,458
are you planning
on going into the holodeck?

632
00:36:19,500 --> 00:36:22,583
I thought I might.
Would you like to join me?

633
00:36:22,625 --> 00:36:25,333
Could you postpone our departure
for just five minutes, sir?

634
00:36:27,041 --> 00:36:29,667
No problem.

635
00:36:33,667 --> 00:36:35,625
You said you had
responsibilities.

636
00:36:35,667 --> 00:36:37,500
What exactly
did you mean?

637
00:36:37,542 --> 00:36:39,834
You know about
my mother's cousin.

638
00:36:39,875 --> 00:36:42,458
The girl from San Antonio
I told you about?

639
00:36:44,375 --> 00:36:46,750
(<i> gasping</i> )
Jimmy.

640
00:36:52,875 --> 00:36:55,583
(<i> sighing</i> )
I'm as jumpy
as Haircut Lapinski

641
00:36:55,625 --> 00:36:57,166
trying to land
on a fraction.

642
00:36:57,208 --> 00:36:59,000
Sorry to bother you,
Captain.

643
00:36:59,041 --> 00:37:00,792
Captain?
Call me Dix.

644
00:37:00,834 --> 00:37:02,166
Sorry to bother you,
Dix,

645
00:37:02,208 --> 00:37:04,166
But our two passengers
have awakened.

646
00:37:04,208 --> 00:37:05,959
Oh, then it's time
for me to go.

647
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:07,667
What about Jimmy Cuzzo?

648
00:37:07,709 --> 00:37:10,000
You can't leave Rex
to face him alone.

649
00:37:10,041 --> 00:37:12,291
I'll be back before
Jimmy Cuzzo arrives.

650
00:37:12,333 --> 00:37:14,083
I guarantee,
it will be taken care of.

651
00:37:14,125 --> 00:37:15,583
Just relax.
Your friends have time

652
00:37:15,625 --> 00:37:17,959
for one drink,
haven't they, Dix?

653
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:20,750
Oh, yes, of course.
One more round.

654
00:37:25,834 --> 00:37:27,041
These are
my associates.

655
00:37:27,083 --> 00:37:30,625
This is, uh, "Nails,"
from Chicago,

656
00:37:30,667 --> 00:37:32,959
and this is, uh...
Carlos.

657
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:34,291
From South America.

658
00:37:34,333 --> 00:37:36,166
This is Madeline,
my secretary.

659
00:37:36,208 --> 00:37:38,417
And I want you
to meet Rex...

660
00:37:38,458 --> 00:37:40,542
you know, I don't think
I ever heard your last name.

661
00:37:40,583 --> 00:37:42,625
Hmm. Don't think
I have one.

662
00:37:42,667 --> 00:37:44,166
Just Rex,
that's all.

663
00:37:44,208 --> 00:37:45,834
So fellas, tell me
your troubles.

664
00:37:45,875 --> 00:37:47,959
Well troubles,
we've got some, Captain.

665
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:50,083
It seems that a certain woman,
both wealthy and beautiful,

666
00:37:50,125 --> 00:37:52,542
now thinks that she is
going to marry<i> me.</i>

667
00:37:52,583 --> 00:37:54,792
REX:
She's got looks
and bucks?

668
00:37:54,834 --> 00:37:58,667
Sounds like you've got
yourself one heck of a deal.

669
00:38:02,500 --> 00:38:06,834
Oh, my fiance just has
to see how I look in this.

670
00:38:06,875 --> 00:38:08,917
Come along, Homn.

671
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:17,792
Hello, uh...
computer?

672
00:38:17,834 --> 00:38:20,417
Is Commander Riker
still on the bridge?

673
00:38:20,458 --> 00:38:23,917
Negative. Riker is currently
in Holodeck 3.

674
00:38:23,959 --> 00:38:27,458
Uh, um, holodeck?
Uh, where is that?

675
00:38:27,500 --> 00:38:30,417
Follow the com-panel lights.
They will lead you there.

676
00:38:30,458 --> 00:38:32,834
Com--
Oh. Oh!

677
00:38:32,875 --> 00:38:34,792
Oh!

678
00:38:40,333 --> 00:38:42,375
Good God, what's that?

679
00:38:49,625 --> 00:38:52,375
I bet that's the broad
with the big bucks.

680
00:38:52,417 --> 00:38:54,500
Hey come on over here,
darling.

681
00:38:54,542 --> 00:38:56,083
I've got the best
stool in the house

682
00:38:56,125 --> 00:38:57,834
saved for you.

683
00:39:01,083 --> 00:39:04,542
So this is where you've
been hiding, Jean-Luc.

684
00:39:04,583 --> 00:39:05,959
I'm surprised you let
this part

685
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:07,208
of the ship
get this dirty.

686
00:39:07,250 --> 00:39:09,625
Oh, relax,
Commander.

687
00:39:09,667 --> 00:39:12,166
You've been making your
true feelings quite clear.

688
00:39:12,208 --> 00:39:16,166
Obviously, you feel
unable to handle me.

689
00:39:16,208 --> 00:39:18,125
Anyway, why would
a beautiful

690
00:39:18,166 --> 00:39:19,792
high-class lady
like yourself

691
00:39:19,834 --> 00:39:22,834
want to hook up
with a mug like that?

692
00:39:22,875 --> 00:39:25,125
You're too good for him
if you ask me.

693
00:39:25,166 --> 00:39:28,000
You are a very
interesting person.

694
00:39:28,041 --> 00:39:29,750
You're not so bad
yourself.

695
00:39:29,792 --> 00:39:34,208
In fact, you're as much class
as this joint's ever seen.

696
00:39:34,250 --> 00:39:36,959
Here.
On the house.

697
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:40,625
It's French...
well, almost.

698
00:39:40,667 --> 00:39:42,500
This is the most
remarkable man.

699
00:39:42,542 --> 00:39:45,625
I've never met anyone
like him.

700
00:39:45,667 --> 00:39:48,083
I don't suppose
you have.

701
00:39:48,125 --> 00:39:49,792
He's strong.

702
00:39:49,834 --> 00:39:53,083
I get no thoughts
from him at all, nothing.

703
00:39:53,125 --> 00:39:54,959
Well I've never known
a man so able

704
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:58,333
to keep his true
feelings completely hidden.

705
00:39:58,375 --> 00:40:01,750
That's because--
No man has ever...

706
00:40:01,792 --> 00:40:04,166
been such a mystery to me.

707
00:40:04,208 --> 00:40:06,875
I usually know their thoughts
before they do.

708
00:40:06,917 --> 00:40:09,417
But not with me, huh?

709
00:40:09,458 --> 00:40:11,709
No.

710
00:40:11,750 --> 00:40:14,959
And I never realized
how erotic that could be.

711
00:40:18,208 --> 00:40:22,333
Um... carry my beverage
to that table.

712
00:40:23,417 --> 00:40:25,959
We have some things
to discuss.

713
00:40:52,417 --> 00:40:55,041
Should we tell her?

714
00:40:55,083 --> 00:40:56,542
(<i> sighing )</i>

715
00:40:56,583 --> 00:40:59,041
I think it would be
only fair...

716
00:40:59,083 --> 00:41:02,083
but let's
allow her the moment.

717
00:41:05,208 --> 00:41:07,875
<i>(shouting</i> )

718
00:41:07,917 --> 00:41:09,375
Worf, the vermicula.

719
00:41:09,417 --> 00:41:11,583
(<i> shouting</i> )

720
00:41:18,417 --> 00:41:20,792
Pulaski to Captain Picard.

721
00:41:20,834 --> 00:41:22,166
Go ahead, doctor.

722
00:41:22,208 --> 00:41:24,667
Our passengers are
on their... feet.

723
00:41:24,709 --> 00:41:25,792
Understood.

724
00:41:25,834 --> 00:41:27,583
We better get
to the bridge.

725
00:41:27,625 --> 00:41:29,417
What's their condition?

726
00:41:29,458 --> 00:41:30,750
Hungry.

727
00:41:33,834 --> 00:41:36,542
Would you like to be shown
to your rooms?

728
00:41:48,333 --> 00:41:50,667
Are you coming,
Mrs. Troi?

729
00:41:50,709 --> 00:41:53,875
Uh, not just yet.

730
00:41:53,917 --> 00:41:57,083
Tell William that
I'm sorry,

731
00:41:57,125 --> 00:41:59,500
but Rex and I are
getting married.

732
00:42:02,125 --> 00:42:04,208
Mrs. Troi, your government
expects me

733
00:42:04,250 --> 00:42:07,417
to deliver you to
the conference on time,

734
00:42:07,458 --> 00:42:10,166
and that's what I intend
to do.

735
00:42:10,208 --> 00:42:12,834
Pity.

736
00:42:12,875 --> 00:42:15,667
Duty calls,
darling.

737
00:42:15,709 --> 00:42:18,500
But I'll be back
for you later.

738
00:42:19,709 --> 00:42:21,542
PICARD:
Mrs. Troi,
there is something

739
00:42:21,583 --> 00:42:23,667
you ought to know
about Rex.

740
00:42:23,709 --> 00:42:25,041
Oh?

741
00:42:34,500 --> 00:42:37,583
Imagine, allowing me
to go on like that

742
00:42:37,625 --> 00:42:41,333
with that man
who doesn't even exist.

743
00:42:41,375 --> 00:42:43,500
But you always say you
like surprises, Mother.

744
00:42:43,542 --> 00:42:44,875
Hmm.

745
00:42:47,709 --> 00:42:49,000
Why are they still here?

746
00:42:50,959 --> 00:42:52,625
We thought since you were
going to the same conference,

747
00:42:52,667 --> 00:42:54,333
you might like to beam down
with the other delegates.

748
00:42:54,375 --> 00:42:57,375
Oh, they're not delegates,
those two are assassins.

749
00:42:57,417 --> 00:43:00,166
That is an outrage!
Lies!

750
00:43:00,208 --> 00:43:03,000
We demand you transport us
at once.

751
00:43:03,041 --> 00:43:04,417
Don't bother
to deny it.

752
00:43:04,458 --> 00:43:05,834
Your minds are
so unsophisticated,

753
00:43:05,875 --> 00:43:08,792
I can read your thoughts
in my sleep.

754
00:43:08,834 --> 00:43:10,333
Oh, their robes
are lined with ultritium.

755
00:43:10,375 --> 00:43:11,709
Highly explosive,

756
00:43:11,750 --> 00:43:14,291
virtually undetectable
by your transporter.

757
00:43:16,291 --> 00:43:18,208
She is correct, sir.

758
00:43:18,250 --> 00:43:20,417
I am detecting large
amounts of ultritium.

759
00:43:20,458 --> 00:43:21,709
Well, of course you are.
They were planning

760
00:43:21,750 --> 00:43:23,875
on blowing up
the entire conference.

761
00:43:24,959 --> 00:43:26,417
Mr. Worf,
take them to level 5.

762
00:43:26,458 --> 00:43:28,458
Disarm them.
Hold them for questioning.

763
00:43:28,500 --> 00:43:30,583
Aye, sir.

764
00:43:47,542 --> 00:43:50,125
Ah, well, I didn't
find a mate,

765
00:43:50,166 --> 00:43:51,792
but I did save
the conference,

766
00:43:51,834 --> 00:43:54,250
as well as
your reputations.

767
00:43:54,291 --> 00:43:56,500
All in a day's work,
I suppose.

768
00:43:56,542 --> 00:43:59,000
Good-bye, Mrs. Troi...

769
00:43:59,041 --> 00:44:01,750
and, thank you.

770
00:44:07,458 --> 00:44:10,291
PICARD:
Energize, Chief O'Brien.

771
00:44:13,834 --> 00:44:15,583
Jean-Luc...

772
00:44:15,625 --> 00:44:18,458
shame on you for
thinking such a thing.
